content: I have found it often successful to omit the password. This is because Google assigns a password after verification.

content: My first thought would be to check SMTP server and verify that you have authentication set properly. That is, the server may not be recognizing that you are a legitimate user.
creator: davidsk

content: You need to mark those false positives as 'Not Junk' to train the filter, and to avoid those messages marked as Junk again. This way Thunderbird also moves them automatically back to the Inbox. https://support.mozilla.org/en-US/kb/thunderbird-and-junk-spam-messages#w_tell-thunderbird-what-is-not-junk
creator: christ1

content: Perhaps post a screen shot of what you do see. On V102 I see it as the very first think on the toolbar on the right, but if you don't have the toolbar enabled then it is possible you really can not see many things, not just get mail.
